******
[2] United Kingdom
Date: Tue 24 May 2022 11:03 EDT
Source: Daily Mail [abridged, edited]
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-10849889/UK-detects-FOURTEEN-monkeypox-cases.html


Another 14 monkeypox patients have been spotted in England as the tropical virus continues to sweep the world amid fears it may have mutated to spread easier between humans. UK Health Security Agency bosses (UKHSA) have now confirmed 71 cases in the unprecedented global outbreak. At least one child has been sickened so far -- but no one has died. Officials have also warned the worst may still be to come.

Officials said a "notable proportion" have occurred among gay and bisexual men but have not provided an exact breakdown. No gender or age details have been shared either. Dr Susan Hopkins, the UKHSA's chief medical adviser, said new monkeypox cases were being spotted "promptly" due to "extensive surveillance and contact tracing networks."

There are 19 countries across the world -- mainly in Europe -- that have already detected the smallpox-like virus, sparking concerns it may have learned to spread easier among humans. Infections are only detected sporadically outside of west and central Africa, where the virus is endemic in animals. Although, imported outbreaks have always fizzled out naturally after a few cases.

Fears were fuelled today [24 May 2022] after analysis of the 1st few sickened patients suggested the virus has evolved "far more" than expected. Portuguese scientists warned an "evolutionary jump" -- like what happened with COVID -- may have created a "hyper-mutated virus."

Health chiefs are alarmed about the cluster of cases. Yesterday [23 May 2022] experts warned that monkeypox could spread to pets and wildlife and become endemic in Europe. A WHO official yesterday claimed the leading theory explaining the spread of the disease was sexual behaviour at 2 raves held in Belgium and Spain.

And Dr. David Heymann, who formerly headed the WHO's emergencies department, said the monkeypox outbreak was a "random event" that might be explained by sexual behaviour at 2 recent events in Spain and Belgium. The Gran Canarian pride festival, held between 5-15 May [2022] and attended by 80 000 people from Britain and across Europe, is being investigated after being linked to numerous monkeypox cases.

UKHSA teams are contacting people considered to be high-risk contacts of confirmed cases and advising them to self-isolate at home for 3 weeks and avoid contact with children. They are also being offered the Imvanex vaccine, which was designed for smallpox. Although not purposefully made for monkeypox, the jab -- made by Danish-based Bavarian Nordic -- is up to 85% effective because the 2 viruses are so similar.

[Byline: Emily Craig]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[The report of a monkeypox (MPX) virus infection in a child is new. Previous reports of MPX outside of Africa during this outbreak indicate that the cases are in adult men and one woman. A positive case of monkeypox has been confirmed in Hertfordshire, health chiefs have said. What is believed to be the county's 1st case is now one of 20 confirmed in England as fears continue to grow over the disease (https://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/news/20159329.monkeypox-case-confirmed-hertfordshire/). Presumably, this case is one of the new cases reported in the UK. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Portugal
Date: Mon 23 May 2022
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/portugal-reports-14-additional-confirmed-monkeypox-cases-22892/


In a follow-up on the monkeypox clusters in Portugal, the Directorate-General for Health (DGS) informs that 14 more cases of human infection by monkeypox virus have been confirmed in Portugal, with 37 confirmed cases so far in the North, Lisbon and Tagus Valley and Algarve regions.

The new cases were confirmed by the National Institute of Health Doctor Ricardo Jorge (INSA). Among the available samples, the West African clade (subgroup of the virus), which is the least aggressive, was identified through sequencing.

The identified cases remain under clinical follow-up, and are stable and on an outpatient basis. Epidemiological investigations of suspected cases that are being detected are ongoing, with the aim of identifying transmission chains and potential new cases and their respective contacts.

Individuals with ulcerative lesions, rash, palpable lymph nodes, possibly accompanied by fever, chills, headache, muscle pain and tiredness, should seek medical advice.

Measures to be implemented in case of suspicious symptoms are reinforced, and individuals must refrain from direct physical contact with other people and from sharing clothing, towels, sheets and personal objects while skin lesions are present, at any stage, or other symptoms.

