[5] Czech Republic ex Belgium
Date: Tue 24 May 2022 22:15 CET
Source: Channel News Asia [edited]
https://www.channelnewsasia.com/world/czech-republic-detects-its-first-case-monkeypox-2704161


The Czech Republic detected its 1st case of monkeypox on Tuesday [24 May 2022] in a woman returning from a festival in Belgium, officials said on Tuesday. The patient was being treated at Prague's Central Military Hospital, the head of the Czech Infectious Medicine Society (SIL) Pavel Dlouhy said, confirming the case, which had earlier been reported by news website Seznam Zpravy.

The National Institute of Public Health (SZU) said a sample from one of 3 people tested had been positive, although final testing results would be confirmed next week. The 2 other suspected patients' tests were also still being worked on, it said.

It said the 1st patient had attended a music festival in Antwerp at the start of May [2022] and began showing symptoms after her return. Several other European countries have reported their 1st confirmed or suspected cases of monkeypox.

The outbreaks are raising alarm because monkeypox, which spreads through close contact and was first found in monkeys, mostly occurs in west and central Africa, and only very occasionally spreads elsewhere.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[This is the 1st report of a female case in the current monkeypox (MPX) outbreak. The specifics of how she might have acquired her MPX virus infection are not given. - Mod.TY]

******
[6] Slovenia ex Canary Islands, Spain
Date: Tue 24 May 2022 07:49 EDT
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/slovenia-reports-first-case-monkeypox-infection-media-2022-05-24/


Slovenia's health authorities on Tuesday [24 May 2022] confirmed the alpine country's 1st case of monkeypox infection in a traveller who had returned from the Canary Islands in Spain. The man was not hospitalised because he was infected by a mild version of the West African strain of the viral disease, Mario Fafangel, the head of the national Centre for Infectious Diseases, told a news conference.

Fafangel said he believed the chain of transmission in Slovenia would be stopped quickly, adding that people who have been in contact with an infected person should be on alert over the next 21 days. There was no need for the wider population to get vaccinated, he added, except for those handling the virus in laboratories.

[Byline: Daria Sito-Sucic]

