[13] Vaccine status
Date: Mon 23 May 2022
Source: The New York Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/23/health/monkeypox-vaccines.html


As more than a dozen countries grapple with outbreaks of monkeypox, health officials worldwide are rushing to assess reserves of vaccines and treatments that may be needed to contain the spread.

The US emergency stockpile holds 2 vaccines approved by the Food and Drug Administration that could be used to contain monkeypox, officials at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) told reporters on Monday [23 May 2022].

The stockpile contains more than 100 million doses of the original smallpox vaccine. But that vaccine is associated with side effects and shouldn't be given to certain patients, including those who are immunocompromised.

A newer vaccine, called Jynneos, was approved in 2019 for prevention of both smallpox and monkeypox. More than 1000 doses are held in the stockpile, Dr. Jennifer McQuiston, a deputy director at the CDC, said.

The situation overseas is more concerning. As of Monday [23 May 2022], there were more than 100 confirmed cases in 14 countries outside Africa, and dozens more under investigation. That day, the European Center for Disease Prevention and Control urged health officials in Europe to assess the availability of smallpox vaccines, antivirals and personal protective equipment.

The World Health Organization is holding stockpiles of about 31 million smallpox vaccine doses, but they may have lost some potency in the decades since they were made.

In any event, mass immunization campaigns are unlikely in any country, including the United States, several experts said. And the outbreaks are unlikely to warrant such a campaign.

Instead, officials may recommend immunizing a circle of close contacts around those found to be infected -- an approach called ring vaccination that has been used to suppress other outbreaks of rare diseases.

In addition to vaccines for prevention, the United States has procured more than 2 million doses of an antiviral pill called tecovirimat, which is approved to treat smallpox in those who become infected, according to the CDC. The agency is also working with the drug's manufacturer to develop an intravenous form.

[Byline: Apoorva Mandavilli]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[Drugs for treatment are available. Tecovirimat (Tpoxx), is approved in the US for treating smallpox in both an oral form (https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/drugInfo.cfm?setid=fce826ab-4d6a-4139-a2ee-a304a913a253) and an intravenous form (https://www.precisionvaccinations.com/vaccines/tpoxx-smallpox-treatment). In the EU, tecovirimat is also indicated for monkeypox (https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/EPAR/tecovirimat-siga and https://www.siga.com/wp-content/themes/sigahba/TPOXX-Fact-Sheet.pdf). - Mod.ML]

******
[14] Spread to pets
Date: Tue 24 May 2022 12:08 EDT
Source: Daily Mail [abridged, edited]
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-10848407/Monkeypox-endemic-Europe-spreads-PETS-Health-chiefs-stark-warning.html


Monkeypox could spread to pets and wildlife and become endemic in Europe, health officials warned yesterday [23 May 2022].

In Africa, where monkeypox is endemic, or well established, the virus is often in rodents, including squirrels and dormice. [These are suspected but not proven reservoir species. The pouched rat _Crycetomys gambiensis_ is experimentally susceptible to infection with MPX virus, but objective evidence of maintenance of the virus in nature by them, rope squirrels and door mice is lacking. - Mod.TY]

The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) said rodents and squirrels could be "suitable hosts" and a "spillover event," where the virus spreads from people to pets to wildlife, could see monkeypox become endemic in Europe.

The report states: "Currently, little is known about the suitability of European peri-domestic (mammalian) animal species to serve as a host for monkeypox virus. However, rodents, and particularly species of the family of Sciuridae (squirrels) are likely to be suitable hosts, more so than humans (see disease background), and transmission from humans to (pet) animals is theoretically possible. Such a spillover event could potentially lead to the virus establishing in European wildlife and the disease becoming an endemic zoonosis."

However, it said the probability of this happening was "very low."

[Byline: Victoria Allen and John Ely]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[The likelihood of MPX virus infecting pets with ongoing transmission to wild mammals such as squirrels is unknown. The susceptibility of pet mammals has not been determined, nor has the susceptibility of wild rodents with which the pets might be in contact. Spillover of the virus to wild mammals and maintenance in them is very speculative at this point and will remain so until laboratory studies of susceptibility or evidence of infection in wild populations has been determined. When MPX virus was introduced into the USA in rodents imported from Ghana, it spread to pet prairie dogs in contact with these imported rodents and then onward to their owners. There was no transmission from these infected prairie dogs or infected people on to wild squirrels, although grey and fox squirrels were common in the localities where infected people and prairie dogs were found. - Mod.TY]

